result.execSummary:
The defendant Nicholas J Jablonski was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Battery [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(1).
  • Disorderly Conduct [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse], a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Reserve Judge Neal Nettesheim presiding for Branch IV
Defendant Nicholas J Jablonski in court with Attorney Jonathan A. Lavoy.   ADA Theresa Beck appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

Maximum penalties recited; Constitutional rights reviewed; plea of " No Contest " entered on Counts #2 and #3; factual basis stipulated; the Court accepts the plea, finds Defendant guilty, and orders Judgment of Conviction entered.

On Motion of the State, the Court reads-in and dismisses Count #1.
Sentencing arguments given by Counsel
Statement made by Victim
Statement made by Mr. Jablonski

On Counts #2 and #3, the Court withholds sentence, and places Defendant on Probation for 2 years, with conditions:

--to undergo AODA assessment and follow through with recommended treatment per Agent
--to undergo any other assessment, treatment or counseling as deemed appropriate by the Agent
--no possesssion of any dangerous weapon
--complete a Certified Batterers' Intervention programming, if directed by DOC
--no acts or threats or violence against any person
--no possession or ingestion of alcohol
--no presence in bars, taverns, or liquor stores
--maintain absolute sobriety
--On Count #2: to pay costs of $243 plus the $200 DNA surcharge plus $100 domestic abuse surcharge
--On Count #3: to pay costs of $243 plus the $200 DNA surcharge plus $100 domestic abuse surcharge

The Court determines that Mr. Jablonski has previously submitted a DNA sample.
